Section 125 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, 1973 (CrPC) deals with the order for maintenance of wives, children, and parents. It states:

"125. Order for maintenance of wives, children and parents.- 
(1) If any person having sufficient means neglects or refuses to maintain— 
    (a) his wife, unable to maintain herself, or
    (b) his legitimate or illegitimate minor child, whether married or not, unable to maintain itself, or
    (c) his legitimate or illegitimate child (not being a married daughter) who has attained majority, where such child is, by reason of any physical or mental abnormality or injury, unable to maintain itself, or
    (d) his father or mother, unable to maintain himself or herself,
a Magistrate of the first class may, upon proof of such neglect or refusal, order such person to make a monthly allowance for the maintenance of his wife or such child, father or mother, at such monthly rate as the Magistrate thinks fit, and to pay the same to such person as the Magistrate may from time to time direct.

(2) The Magistrate shall, in making the order under sub-section (1), consider the following factors, namely:— 
    (a) the income of the person against whom the order is proposed to be made;
    (b) the income of the wife or the child or the father or the mother, as the case may be, against whom the order is proposed to be made;
    (c) the earning capacity of the person against whom the order is proposed to be made;
    (d) the number of persons the person against whom the order is proposed to be made is under a legal obligation to maintain;
    (e) the standard of living of the person against whom the order is proposed to be made;
    (f) the age of the wife, if she happens to be old or unable to maintain herself;
    (g) any other factor which, in the opinion of the Magistrate, is relevant in deciding the application.

(3) The order shall be made in the following manner, namely:— 
    (a) the Magistrate shall make an order for the monthly allowance, which may be for the maintenance of the wife or the child, or the father or the mother, as the case may be;
    (b) the Magistrate may, from time to time, vary, modify or rescind the order for the monthly allowance;
    (c) the Magistrate may, if necessary, order the person against whom the order is made to pay a lump sum in addition to the monthly allowance;
    (d) the Magistrate may, if necessary, order the person against whom the order is made to pay the expenses of the proceeding under this section;
    (e) the Magistrate may impose such conditions or restrictions as he may deem fit in the interest of the wife, or the child, or the father or the mother, as the case may be.

(4) The Magistrate may, during the pendency of the proceeding regarding monthly allowance for the maintenance under this section, order such person to make an interim monthly allowance for the maintenance of his wife or such child, father or mother, and the expenses of the proceeding, as the Magistrate thinks fit, and to pay the same to such person as the Magistrate may from time to time direct.

(5) The Magistrate, if satisfied that there is a change in the circumstances of any person, for whose maintenance an order under this section has been made, may, at any time, make a new order for the maintenance of such person, or may alter or rescind the order relating to the maintenance of such person, as he thinks fit."

This section provides for the maintenance of wives, children, and parents who are unable to maintain themselves, and outlines the factors to be considered by the Magistrate in making such an order.

Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, deals with interim measures by a court. It states that a party may, before or during arbitral proceedings or at any time after the making of the arbitral award but before it is enforced, apply to a court for an interim measure of protection. 

The court may grant the following interim measures:
- to preserve the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take interim custody of the subject-matter of the dispute or to appoint a person to take such custody;
- to appoint a receiver to manage the subject-matter of the dispute;
- to take other interim measures for the purpose of preserving evidence or to prevent the frustration of the arbitration proceedings.

(Section 9, Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996)

Section 17 of the Registration Act, 1908, in India states that certain documents must be registered. It reads: 

"Section 17. Documents of which registration is compulsory.- 
(1) The following documents shall be registered, namely: 
(a) instruments of gift of immovable property;
(b) other non-testamentary instruments which purport or operate to create, declare, assign, limit or extinguish, whether in present or in future, any right, title or interest, whether vested or contingent, of the value of one hundred rupees and upwards, to or in immovable property;
(c) non-testamentary instruments which acknowledge the receipt or payment of any consideration on account of the creation, declaration, assignment, limitation or extinction of any such right, title or interest; and
(d) leases of immovable property from year to year, or for any term exceeding one year, or reserving a yearly rent;
(e) non-testamentary instruments transferring or assigning any decree or order of a Court or any award when such decree, order or award gives the transferee a right, title or interest in any immovable property of the value of one hundred rupees and upwards."

This section essentially mandates the registration of certain types of documents related to immovable property to ensure their validity and enforceability.

In a murder trial under Indian law, the prosecution must prove the following essential elements beyond reasonable doubt:

1. The death of the victim (Section 299 of the Indian Penal Code, 1860 (IPC));
2. The act of the accused caused the death (Section 299 IPC);
3. The act was done with the intention of causing death or with the knowledge that it is so imminently probable that it must in all probability cause death (Section 299 IPC);
4. The act was done with no exception or justification under law (e.g., self-defense, Section 96-106 IPC).

The prosecution must establish these elements through evidence and prove the accused's guilt beyond reasonable doubt (Section 101 of the Indian Evidence Act, 1872).

Under Section 11 of the Code of Civil Procedure (CPC), 1908, the ingredients of res judicata are:

1. The matter was directly and substantially in issue in the former suit (Section 11(a));
2. The former suit was between the same parties or between parties under whom they or any of them claim (Section 11(b));
3. The parties were litigating under the same title (Section 11(b));
4. The court that decided the former suit was competent to try the subsequent suit (Section 11(c));
5. The matter was heard and finally decided by the court in the former suit (Section 11(d)).

If these conditions are met, the matter is said to be res judicata, or "a thing already judged," and cannot be relitigated in a subsequent suit. (Section 11, CPC, 1908)

A second appeal is maintainable under Section 100 of the Code of Civil Procedure (CPC) when the appeal involves a substantial question of law. According to Section 100(1) of the CPC, a second appeal shall lie from an appellate decree passed by a court if the case involves a substantial question of law. 

Section 100(1) of the CPC states: "Save as otherwise provided in this Court, an appeal shall lie from every decree passed by any Court exercising original jurisdiction to the Court authorized to hear appeals from the decisions of such Court, and the parties to such appeal shall be at liberty to urge all grounds of objection to such decree as could have been urged in the Court of first instance, and the Court of appeal may hear and determine such appeal on any of the following grounds, namely:-

(a) the decision being contrary to law or to some usage having the force of law;
(b) the decision having failed to determine some material issue of law or fact;
(c) a substantial error or defect in the procedure provided by this Code or by any other law for the time being in force which may have produced error or defect in the decision of the case;
and the appeal shall also be heard on the following grounds, namely:-
(d) that there is an error on the face of the record; 
(e) that there is some matter which the Court of first instance had not considered which is relevant to the decision of the case."

However, for a second appeal to be maintainable, the High Court must be satisfied that the case involves a substantial question of law as per Section 100 of the CPC.

Under Section 10 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, specific performance of a contract can be enforced when the following conditions are met:

1. The contract is in writing (Section 10(a));
2. The contract is registered, if registration is required by law (Section 10(b));
3. The contract is of the nature for which specific performance is allowed under the Act (Section 10(c));
4. The plaintiff has performed or is ready and willing to perform his part of the contract (Section 10(d));
5. The defendant has failed to perform his part of the contract (Section 10(e));
6. The contract is not one which can be adequately compensated by damages (Section 10(f));
7. The contract is not one which is voidable under Section 14 of the Act (Section 10(g));
8. The contract is not one which cannot be specifically enforced under Section 14 of the Act (Section 10(h));
9. The contract is one where specific performance would not cause hardship to the defendant (Section 10(i));
10. The contract is one where specific performance would not cause injustice to the defendant (Section 10(j));
11. The contract is one where specific performance is not otherwise barred by law (Section 10(k)).

However, the main conditions under Section 10 are that the contract must be in writing and registered (if required), and the plaintiff must have performed or be ready and willing to perform his part of the contract. 

(See: Section 10, Specific Relief Act, 1963)

Under Section 14 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, the following contracts are not specifically enforceable:

1. Contracts where a party has obtained substituted performance (Section 14(a));
2. Contracts that are determinable or liable to be determined (Section 14(b));
3. Contracts for non-performance of which compensation in money is an adequate relief (Section 14(c));
4. Contracts where the performance would be unfair or inequitable (Section 14(d));
5. Contracts for personal service other than for breach of contract to serve as a partner in a firm (Section 14(e));
6. Contracts for the non-performance of which a remedy is available under other laws (Section 14(f)).

These exceptions are outlined in Section 14 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963.

Under Section 19 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, specific performance of a contract can be enforced against:

1. A party to the contract (Section 19(a));
2. Any other person claiming under him by a title arising subsequent to the contract, except a bona fide purchaser for value without notice (Section 19(b));
3. A person claiming under a title which is voidable under the Contract Act, 1872 (Section 19(c)).

Under Section 31 of the Specific Relief Act, 1963, a written instrument can be cancelled if it is unlawful or useless, or if it has been obtained by misrepresentation, fraud, or coercion. The court may cancel a written instrument in the following circumstances:

1. The instrument is unlawful (Section 31(a));
2. The instrument is useless (Section 31(b));
3. The instrument has been obtained by misrepresentation, fraud, or coercion (Section 31(c));
4. The instrument is voidable under Section 19 or Section 19-A of the Indian Contract Act, 1872 (Section 31(d)).

The court may cancel the instrument on such terms as to compensation, payment, indemnification, or otherwise, as it thinks fit (Section 31).

Under Section 6 of the Transfer of Property Act, 1882, the following kinds of property cannot be transferred:

1. The interest of a lessee under a lease of immovable property (Section 6(a));
2. The interest of a tenant under a tenancy agreement, where the tenant has no right to assign or sublet (Section 6(b));
3. An interest in a property that is held for a public purpose or for the benefit of the public (Section 6(c));
4. A mere right to sue (Section 6(d));
5. A right to future maintenance (Section 6(e));
6. A mere right to revenge (Section 6(f));
7. Any estate which is vested in a person as a trustee or with which he is entrusted for the benefit of another person (Section 6(g) and Section 53, 54, 55, 56, 57 and 58 of the Act also deal with trusts and their transferability);
8. A spes successionis, i.e., a mere chance or expectation of succeeding to property (Section 6(h));
9. A mere right of re-entry for breach of a condition subsequent (Section 6(i)).

These properties are not transferable as they are either inalienable, or their transfer would be against public policy or would defeat the purpose for which they were created.

Under Section 8 of the Transfer of Property Act, 1882, where a transfer is made without consideration, the transferee takes the property subject to all liabilities and obligations that the transferor was subject to at the time of the transfer. However, if the transfer is made for consideration, the transferee takes the property free from all liabilities and obligations that the transferor was subject to at the time of the transfer, except those that are expressly mentioned in the transfer deed or that the transferee had notice of at the time of the transfer.

In essence, Section 8 provides that in the case of a transfer for consideration, the transferee takes the property free from all encumbrances, except those that are:

1. Expressed in the transfer deed (Section 8(a));
2. Implied in the transfer deed (Section 8(b));
3. Known to the transferee at the time of the transfer (Section 8(c)).

This means that the transferee gets all the rights, title, and interest in the property that the transferor had, subject to the exceptions mentioned in Section 8.

Under Section 2(68) of the Companies Act, 2013, a private company is defined as a company that has a minimum paid-up share capital of ₹1 lakh or such higher paid-up share capital as may be prescribed, and which by its articles—

(a) restricts the right to transfer its shares;
(b) except in the case of One Person Company, limits the number of its members to two hundred;
(c) prohibits any invitation to the public to subscribe for any securities of the company.

Under Section 9 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, a party can seek interim measures from the court before, during, or after the arbitration proceedings. These measures include:

1. Appointment of a guardian for a minor or person of unsound mind (Section 9(1)(a));
2. Preservation, interim custody, or sale of any goods which are the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement (Section 9(1)(b));
3. Securing the amount in dispute in the arbitration (Section 9(1)(c));
4. Detention, preservation, or inspection of any property or thing which is the subject-matter of the arbitration agreement (Section 9(1)(d));
5. Interim injunction or the appointment of a receiver (Section 9(1)(e));
6. Such other interim measure of protection as may appear to the court to be just and convenient (Section 9(1)(f)).

These interim measures can be sought by a party to protect its interests and to prevent any prejudice to the arbitration proceedings. (Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, Section 9)

Under Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996, the following orders are appealable:

1. Refusing to refer the parties to arbitration under Section 8 (Order refusing reference to arbitration);
2. Granting or refusing to grant any interim measure under Section 9 (Interim measures by Court);
3. Refusing to enforce a foreign award under Section 36 (Enforcement of foreign awards), after the award has become enforceable under Section 57 (Conditions for enforcement of foreign awards) or has been recognized as enforceable under Section 58 (Conditions for recognition of foreign awards);
4. Setting aside or refusing to set aside an arbitral award under Section 34 (Application for setting aside arbitral award).

These orders are appealable to the Court as per Section 37 of the Arbitration and Conciliation Act, 1996.

Under Section 3 of the Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005, domestic violence is defined as any act of commission or omission which aids or abets the commission of, or which is an incident of, domestic violence, including but not limited to:

(a) physical abuse;
(b) sexual abuse;
(c) verbal and emotional abuse;
(d) economic abuse; and
(e) harassment with the intent to coerce the victim to meet any unlawful demand for any dowry or other property or valuable security.

This definition is provided under Section 3 of the Act, which aims to protect women from domestic violence in India.

Under Section 19 of the Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act, 2005, the following residence orders are available:

1. Restraining the respondent from dispossessing or in any other manner disturbing the possession of the shared household (Section 19(a));
2. Directing the respondent to remove himself from the shared household (Section 19(b));
3. Restraining the respondent or any of his relatives from entering any portion of the shared household in which the petitioner resides (Section 19(c));
4. Restraining the respondent from alienating any assets in the shared household (Section 19(d));
5. Directing the respondent to secure same level of alternative accommodation for the petitioner (Section 19(e)).

These orders aim to provide protection to the victim of domestic violence and ensure her right to residence in the shared household.

